      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-code-verification",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification via benchmark cases",
        "description": "Solver passes ASME V&V 20 benchmark cases for incompressible Navier-Stokes including lid-driven cavity and backward-facing step. Results within published tolerance bands."
      },
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent has been verified against standard CFD benchmark cases (lid-driven cavity Re=1000, backward-facing step Re=800) with errors below 1% relative to published reference solutions. These benchmarks confirm correct implementation of the incompressible RANS solver used in this study."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/discretization-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "GCI < 5% on hemolysis index QoI",
        "description": "Grid Convergence Index (GCI) computed on three systematically refined meshes (2.1M, 5.8M, 14.2M cells). GCI on relative hemolysis index must be below 5% at the worst-case operating point."
      },
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed using GCI methodology (Celik et al. 2008). GCI on the relative hemolysis index at the 6 L/min, 3500 RPM operating point is 2.3%, well below the 5% threshold. Order of convergence p=1.94, consistent with second-order spatial discretization. Gradation 3 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Experimental boundary conditions documented and matched in CFD",
        "description": "Inlet flow rate, rotational speed, fluid viscosity, and temperature match FDA GCBP experimental protocol within stated tolerances. Boundary condition uncertainty propagated to QoI."
      },
      "rationale": "Experimental test conditions from the FDA GCBP round-robin study (Hariharan et al. 2011) are fully documented. CFD boundary conditions replicate the five flow-speed combinations (2, 3, 4, 5, 6 L/min at 2500 and 3500 RPM) with inlet turbulence intensity set to 5% per experimental characterization. Fluid properties (blood analog, 36% glycerol) matched to within 1% of reported values."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Velocity field agreement within experimental uncertainty bands",
        "description": "CFD velocity profiles at five PIV measurement planes agree with experimental data within ±2 standard deviations of PIV measurement uncertainty at ≥90% of comparison points."
      },
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison of CFD velocity fields against FDA GCBP PIV data (Stewart et al. 2012) shows agreement within ±2 SD of PIV uncertainty at 93% of comparison points across all five operating conditions. Maximum local discrepancy of 12% observed in the volute region, within acceptable range for RANS turbulence modeling at these Reynolds numbers."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI directly maps to clinical hemolysis endpoint",
        "description": "The relative hemolysis index (RH) computed from CFD shear stress history is the same metric used in predicate device comparison and regulatory submission. Correlation with in-vitro hemolysis (normalized index of hemolysis, NIH) documented."
      },
      "rationale": "The primary QoI is the relative hemolysis index (RH) derived from the power-law hemolysis model applied to CFD-predicted shear stress and exposure time. This metric directly corresponds to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate) and has established correlation with in-vitro NIH measurements in the literature (Giersiepen et al., Zhang et al.). The QoI is thus directly relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/relevance-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/relevance-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activities conducted on same device geometry and operating range",
        "description": "Validation experiments use the FDA GCBP geometry and the same five operating points as the COU. No extrapolation beyond validated flow-speed envelope required."
      },
      "rationale": "All validation activities were performed on the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry at the same five flow-speed operating points defined in the COU. No interpolation or extrapolation beyond the validated envelope is required for the worst-case hemolysis identification task. The validation domain fully encompasses the COU application domain."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/numerical-solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Iterative convergence to residual < 1e-5 with monitored QoI stabilization",
        "description": "All residuals (continuity, momentum, turbulence) converge below 1e-5. Hemolysis index QoI monitored over final 500 iterations and varies by less than 0.5%."
      },
      "rationale": "Steady-state RANS simulations converged to residuals below 1e-5 for all equations. The hemolysis index QoI was monitored over the final 500 iterations and showed variation less than 0.3%, confirming iterative convergence. Gradation 2 achieved, exceeding MRL 2 requirement of Gradation 1."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error as defined in ASME V&V 40 pertains to errors introduced by incorrect operator use of a medical device in a clinical setting. This COU concerns a computational model used by trained simulation engineers in a controlled regulatory submission workflow, not a device deployed in clinical practice. There is no patient-facing interaction with the CFD model output; the model produces a comparative hemolysis index reviewed by engineers and regulatory scientists. Accordingly, the use-error factor as scoped in V&V 40 for device-in-use scenarios does not apply to this computational credibility assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Turbulence model selection justified against experimental data",
        "description": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on published comparative studies for rotating blood pump CFD. Model form uncertainty estimated via comparison with k-epsilon realizable results; difference in RH index < 8%."
      },
      "rationale": "The SST k-omega turbulence model was selected based on its established performance for rotating machinery flows with adverse pressure gradients, supported by published comparative studies for blood pump CFD (Garon & Farinas 2004, Bludszuweit 1995). Model form uncertainty was estimated by comparing SST k-omega and realizable k-epsilon predictions; the resulting difference in relative hemolysis index was 6.4%, within the 8% acceptance bound. Gradation 2 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Material properties and geometry inputs traceable to measurement sources",
        "description": "Blood analog fluid properties (density, viscosity) sourced from NIST-traceable measurements. Pump geometry digitized from FDA GCBP CAD file with dimensional verification against physical measurements within 0.05 mm."
      },
      "rationale": "Fluid properties for the 36% glycerol blood analog are sourced from NIST-traceable viscometry measurements reported in the FDA GCBP study protocol. Pump geometry was digitized from the official FDA GCBP CAD file; dimensional verification against coordinate measuring machine measurements of the physical model confirms agreement within 0.03 mm across all critical dimensions. Input uncertainty for fluid viscosity (±2%) and geometry (±0.03 mm) was propagated to the hemolysis QoI via Latin Hypercube sampling."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The test-samples factor in ASME V&V 40 addresses variability in physical test specimens used for validation, including manufacturing tolerances and lot-to-lot variation. In this assessment, the validation experiments were conducted using the FDA GCBP, which is a single, precisely manufactured reference geometry distributed by FDA for the explicit purpose of CFD validation benchmarking. There is no specimen-to-specimen variability to characterize; all participating laboratories used geometrically identical pumps fabricated to the FDA specification. Accordingly, the test-samples factor is not applicable to this standardized benchmark validation scenario."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/equivalency-input-parameters",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "CFD boundary conditions match experimental conditions within stated tolerances",
        "description": "All CFD input parameters (flow rate ±0.1 L/min, rotational speed ±10 RPM, fluid viscosity ±2%) match experimental conditions within the tolerances documented in the FDA GCBP experimental protocol."
      },
      "rationale": "A systematic equivalency assessment was performed comparing CFD model inputs against the experimental conditions reported in the FDA GCBP validation dataset. Flow rates were matched within ±0.05 L/min (half the acceptance tolerance), rotational speeds within ±5 RPM, and fluid viscosity within ±1.2%. These equivalencies were verified against the original experimental protocol documentation. No parameter required adjustment beyond stated tolerances, confirming full equivalency at Gradation 2."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou1-cpb-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment for the FDA GCBP CFD hemolysis model under CPB conditions is accepted at Medium assurance level. All 11 assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels for Model Risk Level 2. Discretization error (GCI 2.3%) and numerical solver error (residuals < 1e-5, QoI variation < 0.3%) exceed minimum requirements. Output comparison against FDA GCBP PIV data shows 93% of points within ±2 SD of experimental uncertainty. The two not-applicable factors (Use error, Test samples) are excluded on documented technical grounds: use error does not apply to a controlled computational workflow without patient-facing deployment, and test-sample variability is not applicable given the standardized single-geometry FDA GCBP benchmark. The relative hemolysis index QoI is directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 vs. predicate) and has established clinical correlation. Validation activities fully encompass the COU operating envelope with no extrapolation required. The structured evidence supports the claim that the CFD model can reliably identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for this Class II CPB device.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
